message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The photomicrograph shows a well-defined border with cells with abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm, which is characteristic of oncocytoma. Clear cell renal carcinoma would have a more solid appearance, while nephroblastoma (also known as Wilms tumor) is more common in children. Angiomyolipoma would show a mixture of adipose tissue, smooth muscle cells, and blood vessels on microscopic examination.

The photomicrograph of the resected mass shows large eosinophilic cells with abundant granular cytoplasm and small, centrally positioned nuclei, which is characteristic of oncocytoma. Clear cell renal carcinoma and angiomyolipoma show different histological features. Nephroblastoma is a pediatric tumor and is less likely in a 57-year-old patient.

The photomicrograph shows numerous uniform, small, round cells and nests with abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm and prominent central nucleoli, which are consistent with Oncocytoma. Clear cell renal carcinoma has a different histological appearance, with clear cytoplasm, and Nephroblastoma mainly affects young children. Angiomyolipoma has a mixture of adipose tissue, smooth muscle, and thick-walled blood vessels.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The photomicrograph shows a central scar, which is a characteristic feature of oncocytoma. Clear cell renal carcinoma and angiomyolipoma are less likely to have a central scar, and nephroblastoma is usually found in children. The presence of hematuria and a renal mass increase the suspicion for a malignant tumor, but the central scar favors oncocytoma, which is usually a benign tumor.
